    <string name="home_heading5">The Actual Value</string>
    <string name="home_multiline1">The golden ratio (symbol is the Greek letter \"phi\" shown at top) is a special number approximately equal to 1.618.
        It appears many times in geometry, art, architecture and other areas.</string>
    <string name="home_multiline2">We find the golden ratio when we divide a line into two parts so that:
the long part divided by the short part is also equal to the whole length divided by the long part.</string>
    <string name="home_multiline3">This rectangle has been made using the Golden Ratio, Looks like a typical frame for a painting, doesn\'t it?
        Some artists and architects believe the Golden Ratio makes the most pleasing and beautiful shape.</string>
    <string name="home_multiline4">Many buildings and artworks have the Golden Ratio in them, such as the Parthenon in Greece,
        but it is not really known if it was designed that way.</string>
    <string name="home_multiline5">The Golden Ratio is equal to:  1.61803398874989484820... (etc.) The digits just keep on going, with no pattern. In fact the Golden Ratio is known to be an Irrational Number, and I will tell you more about it later.</string>
